# Commit rules

## No AI-tool branding in commits

Do **not** add trailers, co-authors, or signatures attributing commits to
any AI coding tool — Cursor, Claude, Copilot, Cody, or others. This
includes:

- `--trailer "Made with: Cursor"`, `Co-authored-by: Cursor <...>`,
  `Co-authored-by: Claude <...>`, etc.
- Any "Generated by ..." or "Assisted by ..." notes in the commit body.
- Emoji or branding in the subject line that signals AI authorship.

The author is the human who reviewed and accepted the change.

## Reference the work the commit addresses

Commit messages reference, where applicable:

- The spec section the change implements (e.g., `FCMP_PLUS_PLUS.md §4.2`).
- The `docs/FOLLOWUPS.md` item being closed.
- The audit finding being remediated.
- The phase or task in the integration plan.

Bare "fix bug" / "wip" / "address review" commits don't survive
`git log --oneline` review six months later. Be specific about what changed
and why.

## Scope per commit

Per `15-deletion-and-debt.mdc`, "while we're here" changes go in separate
commits. Bisection requires small, scope-respecting commits.

## Subject line

Imperative mood, ≤72 chars. Prefix with the affected subsystem when useful
(`fcmp:`, `wallet:`, `rpc:`, `crypto-pq:`, `economics:`).
